In this paper, we provide matching (up to a constant factor) upper and lower bounds on the degree of polynomials that represent symmetric boolean functions with an error 1/3. Let Γ(<italic>f</italic>)=min{|2<italic>k</italic>–<italic>n</italic>+1|:<italic>f<subscrpt>k</subscrpt></italic> <inline-equation> <f> ≠ </f> </inline-equation><italic>f</italic><subscrpt><italic>k</italic>+ 1</subscrpt> and 0 ≤ <italic>k</italic> ≤ <italic>n</italic> – 1} where <italic>f<subscrpt>i</subscrpt></italic> is the value of <italic>f</italic> on inputs with exactly <italic>i</italic> 1's. We prove that the minimum degree over all the approximating polynomials of <italic>f</italic> is &THgr;((<italic>n</italic>(<italic>n</italic>-Γ(<italic>f</italic>)))<supscrpt>.5</supscrpt>). We apply the techniques and tools from  approximation theory to derive this result.